n period. Seeking to understand the volcano’s place in the larger system of nature, Neapolitans flocked to Vesuvius to examine volcanic phenomena and to collect floral and mineral specimens from the mountainside. In Watching Vesuvius, Cocco argues that this investigation and engagement with Vesuvius was paramount to the development of modern volcanology. He then situates the native experience of Vesuvius in a larger intellectual, cultural, and political context and explains how later eighteenth-century representations of Naples—of its climate and character—grew out of this tradition of natural history. Painting a rich and detailed portrait of Vesuvius and those living in its shadow, Cocco returns the historic volcano to its place in a broader European culture of science, travel, and appreciation of the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aVolcanismxSocial aspectszItalyzNaples. 0aVolcanismzItalyzNaplesxInfluence. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  amount vesuvius, volcano, eruption, natural disasters, pompeii, herculaneum, italy, history, renaissance, pilgrimage, observation, nature, specimens, volcanology, naples, science, travel, nonfiction, humanism, naturalists, geology, imaging, astronomy, lava flows, religion, politics, social change, unrest, revolt, poverty, exoticism, political rivals.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226923734423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226923734/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles